# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carlos-garcía-solórzano
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] The **1948 Amateur World Series** was the 10th edition of the Amateur World Series.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] It was held in Managua, Nicaragua from November 20 through December 12, 1948.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] The usually-powerful Cubans did not field a squad; in the wake of the integration of organized baseball, many top Cuban amateurs had been signed by Major League Baseball teams that had previously refused to sign the darker-skinned Cubans.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] Venezuela also did not send its national team, due to strained relations between the Venezuelan government, led by Rómulo Gallegos, and Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza García.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] Somoza accused the Venezuelan government of promoting revolutionary groups in Central America.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] The democratically-elected Gallegos would be removed from power in a military coup on Nov.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] 24, 1948, midway through the tournament).
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] The first pitch, at the new Estadio Nacional in Managua, was supposed to be thrown by the president of Nicaragua, Víctor Manuel Román y Reyes, but he instead allowed Anastasio Somoza García, head of the National Guard and the country's *de facto* dictator, to throw the first pitch instead.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] Chale Pereira, Nicaraguan president of the International Baseball Federation, was also present.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] After Nicaragua lost a game against Mexico, Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza fired the team's Cuban manager, Juan Ealo, and took over the reins of the team himself.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1948-amateur-world-series] However, the team still limped to a dismal 1–6 record.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1950-amateur-world-series] The **1950 Amateur World Series** was the 11th Amateur World Series (AWS), an international men's amateur baseball tournament.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1950-amateur-world-series] The tournament was sanctioned by the International Baseball Federation (which titled it the Baseball World Cup as of the 1988 tournament).
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1950-amateur-world-series] The tournament took place, for the second time, in Nicaragua, which had also hosted the previous (1948) tournament.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1950-amateur-world-series] Cuba won their fifth AWS title, taking the gold in 1950.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] The **1972 Amateur World Series** was the 20th Amateur World Series (AWS), an international men's amateur baseball tournament.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] The tournament was sanctioned by the International Baseball Federation (FIBA) and took place, for the third time, in Nicaragua, from November 25th to December 5, 1972.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] Cuba won its 12th international championship, and fourth consecutive title; the United States finished with the silver medal for the third time since returning to AWS competition in 1969.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] Nicaragua, the hosts, finished with the bronze for the second consecutive year.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] The tournament occurred just weeks before the devastating 1972 Nicaragua earthquake.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] This led to a controversy where Nicaragua was suspended from FIBA on charges that it had been too late in paying FIBA the tournament revenues, despite the earthquake.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] The suspension of Nicaragua in light of these events was a catalyst for Nicaragua, the United States, and several other baseball federations to leave FIBA and form their own international baseball organization, FEMBA.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] 16 nations participated, the most ever included in an Amateur World Series to date (the previous high had been 13, in 1952).
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] Both Japan and Chinese Taipei made their debuts, becoming the first Asian countries to participate in the tournament.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] Brazil also made it Amateur World Series debut, though after 1972, it would not return to the tournament until 2003 (when it was known as the Baseball World Cup).
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] The Puerto Rico national baseball team was notably managed by Roberto Clemente, a legendary major leaguer with the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-amateur-world-series] Three weeks after the tournament, Clemente was attempting to return to Managua when his flight, carrying foreign aid for earthquake victims, crashed, killing Clemente and four others.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The **1972 Nicaragua earthquake** occurred at 12:29:44 a.m. local time (06:29:44 UTC) on 23 December near Managua, the capital of Nicaragua.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] It had a moment magnitude of 6.3 and a maximum MSK intensity of IX (*Destructive*).
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The epicenter was 28 km (17 mi) northeast of the city centre with a depth of about 10 km (6.2 mi).
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The earthquake caused widespread casualties among Managua's residents: 4,000–11,000 were killed, 20,000 were injured and over 300,000 were left homeless.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Managua, which lies on the southern shore of Lake Xolotlán, near the western coast of Nicaragua, is situated within an active volcanic zone known as the Central American Volcanic Chain.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The city has a long history of volcanic and seismic activity which arise from the relative movements of two crustal plates which intersect near the southwestern border of Central America.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The Cocos plate, located east of the East Pacific Rise, is moving northeastward and is slowly being submerged (subducted) under the Caribbean plate.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The zone of dipping is initiated at the surface of the Middle America Trench, which extends 4 to 5 kilometers deep along the Pacific Coast from Mexico to Costa Rica.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] But rather than a simple crustal movement between the two plates the earthquake was believed to have been caused by a shallow adjustment to geological pressure at the southwestern corner of the Caribbean plate.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The earthquake severely damaged 27 square kilometres (10 sq mi) and destroyed 13 square kilometres (5.0 sq mi) in the city centre.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The majority of the buildings in the city's central business district sustained significant structural damage including a 19-story building, one 15-story building, approximately 5 buildings that were 7 to 9 stories tall and more than 25 buildings that were from 3 to 6 stories tall.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Much of the damage arose from seismic ground movement which occurred within 10–15 seconds of the main shock.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The majority of the factories and smaller buildings were severely damaged.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Many of the houses and small shops were over 40 years old and constructed using a local method called *taquezal* (or *talquezal*), in which the timber framed walls are filled with stone and finished with plaster, covered by roofs of unmortared clay tile.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The design is very susceptible to earthquake damage.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] An estimated 53,000 homes in the city were damaged.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The water and electrical power networks were severely damaged and more than a week after the earthquake only 10% of the city had any working water service.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] One of the most significant geological effects of the earthquake quake was surface faulting.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Examination of the fault lines indicated a lateral motion moving in a northeasterly direction and aftershock data has revealed at least one of the faults extends from the surface to a depth of 8 to 10 kilometers beneath the city of Managua.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Within an hour after the main shock, two aftershocks, one of magnitude 5.0 and the other 5.2, occurred at 1:18 a.m. and 1:20 a.m.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Two-thirds of Managua's 1,000,000 residents were displaced and faced food shortage and disease, and dry-season winds worsened the problem with fires created by the disaster.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Because of the damaging effects of the earthquake, many of the emergency services in the city were operating at a seriously lower level than normal.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The earthquake destroyed all the fire-fighting equipment available, and fires were prevalent in some areas for several days.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] All four main hospitals, which before the disaster had 1,650 beds, were unserviceable.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The Nicaraguan government appealed for aid, and the government accepted aid from countries like the United States and Mexico and some 25 other countries, worth millions of dollars.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Despite this and the magnitude of the devastation, the aid was not distributed well and the ruling Liberal-Conservative Junta, led by President Anastasio Somoza Debayle, was the target of criticism and was accused of stockpiling foreign aid which never reached the victims of the earthquake.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] It was because of these reports that the Puerto Rican baseball star Roberto Clemente chose to personally accompany the fourth of a number of relief flights he had organized.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] That flight crashed on 31 December, killing Clemente among others.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Another difficulty was that much of the material aid donated was inappropriate for the needs of the affected Nicaraguans, including such items as winter clothes (Managua's climate is tropical) and frozen TV dinners.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] It was later claimed that Somoza and his associates had used foreign aid for their own gain.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Opposition to the regime, which had begun to surface before the earthquake, increased quickly among the lower classes and even among members of the upper and middle classes fed up with Somoza's corruption.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] This grew into a revolt that became the Nicaraguan Revolution, in which Somoza was overthrown in 1979.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Because of the extent of the damage, the faulty underground terrain, the misappropriation of aid, and the subsequent revolution and 11-year civil war, much of the city centre remained ruined for almost 20 years.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Reconstruction only began in earnest in the 1990s.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The earthquake changed the face of Managua during its decades of recovery.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] The city center is no longer clearly defined, as buildings have been constructed away from the city center.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] During the massive evacuations, the displaced residents set up camp around water resources and areas that remained somewhat unaffected.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Although Managua remains Central America's second largest capital and metropolitan area, the bulk of its residents reside in barrios or neighborhoods that are of considerable distance from the city center.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1972-nicaragua-earthquake] Today, in place of the large buildings that used to exist in the center, the government set up the "Plaza de la Fe" (Faith Square) in honor of Pope John Paul II.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] The **1973 FEMBA Amateur World Series** was organized by World Amateur Baseball Federation (FEMBA), a splinter organization from the International Baseball Federation (FIBA).
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] The tournament, which ran from November 22 through December 5, 1973, was primarily held in Nicaragua, with some games also held in neighboring Honduras and Costa Rica.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] It was one of two international championships held in 1973, along with the FIBA tournament held in Cuba, amid a period of conflict between the two rival governing bodies of an international baseball.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] Most games were held in various cities in Nicaragua (Masaya, Granada, León, and Chinandega); after opening the series in Granada, Costa Rica and Honduras played the rest of their games in San José and Tegucigalpa, respectively.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] The tournament saw the first international championship for the United States, which defeated Nicaragua in the championship game, an extra innings pitcher's duel between Rich Wortham and Dennis Martínez.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] It was also one of the first international tournaments to use the designated hitter, which had been adopted by the American League of Major League Baseball earlier that year.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] The 1973 FEMBA AWS is retroactively recognized as the 22nd edition of the Amateur World Series ("Amateur World Series XXII"), while the Havana edition is recognized as the 21st; despite this, the Nicaragua tournament started and ended earlier that the one held in Havana.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] Games in Costa Rica were held at the Estadio Antonio Escarré in the capital of San José; in Honduras, they were held at the Parque de Pelota Lempira Reina Zepeda in Tegucigalpa.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] In Nicaragua, games were held at the Estadio Municipal Flor de Caña in Granada, the Estadio Roberto Clemente in Masaya, and the Estadio Efraín Tijerino in Chinandega.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] Nicaragua's largest stadium, the Estadio Nacional General Somoza in Managua, with a capacity of 40,000 spectators, was not used due to damage from the 1972 Nicaragua earthquake.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] This limited ticket sales, as the stadiums in Masaya, Granada, and Chinandega were limited to no more than 11,000 spectators.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] The final game was played in the Nicaraguan city of León.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] The United States was managed by college coach Ron Fraser, who had just steered the Netherlands to the 1973 European Championship.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1973-amateur-world-series-femba] Nicaragua was steered by Argelio Cordoba.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] General elections were held in Nicaragua on 25 February 1990 to elect the President and the members of the National Assembly.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] The result was a victory for the National Opposition Union (UNO), whose presidential candidate Violeta Chamorro surprisingly defeated incumbent president Daniel Ortega of the Sandinista National Liberation Front (FSLN).
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] Sandinistas had held power since the FSLN toppled the Somoza dictatorship in 1979.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] Daniel Ortega was elected President in 1984.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] Chamorro was the editor of the country's largest newspaper, *La Prensa*, which she took over after the assassination of her husband Pedro Joaquín Chamorro Cardenal in 1978.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] A vocal critic of the dictatorship, his murder galvanized support for the Sandinistas against the dictatorship.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] Following the revolution that overthrew Somoza, Violeta Chamorro initially supported the FSLN government, accepting an invitation to join the Junta of National Reconstruction.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] However she soon became disenchanted and resigned, returning to the newspaper and becoming a critic of the FSLN government.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] In 1989 the United States Congress approved $9 million for the promotion of democracy in Nicaragua, of which $2.5 million was set aside for the UNO, in addition to a $5 million grant for the opposition earlier that year.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] Beginning in early 1989 the government held a series of talks with the opposition about reforming electoral and media laws.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] In April 1989 the Electoral Law was reformed, giving the opposition a larger share of public campaign funds, increased access to state run media and permission to receive foreign financing.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] With a diverse coalition of 14 opposition groups, the UNO mainly campaigned on a promise to end the decades of civil war and instability that wracked the country.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] While the FSLN was mainly under controversy for their campaign due to their use of violence.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] Opinion polls leading up to the elections divided along partisan lines, with 10 of 17 polls analyzed in a contemporary study predicting an UNO victory while 7 predicted the Sandinistas would retain power.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] The election was organized by Mariano Fiallos Oyanguren, a law professor and Sandinista who was appointed by the FSLN in 1984 to head the Supreme Electoral Council.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] He faced party pressure to throw the race, specifically to announce at 19:00 on election night that the results of the first four precincts were four victories for the FSLN.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] Instead he chose to read the real results, which split the precincts, with two going to the FSLN and two to the ONU, which went on to win the election.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] Chamorro was elected with just under 55% of the vote.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] Possible explanations for the ONU victory include that the Nicaraguan people were disenchanted with the Ortega government, specifically discontentment with the management of the economy and the hostile posture toward the United States, believing the ONU was more likely to bring peace.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] Additionally, in November 1989, the White House had met with Chamorro on the subject of peace and democracy in Nicaragua and announced that the economic embargo against Nicaragua would end if Chamorro won.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/1990-nicaraguan-general-election] There are also reports of intimidation from the side of the Contras, with a Canadian observer mission claiming that 42 people were killed by the Contras in "election violence" in October 1989.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/carlos-garcía-solórzano] García founded the Nicaraguan Olympic Committee in 1959.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/carlos-garcía-solórzano] As president of the Nicaraguan Baseball Federation (FENIBA), he was responsible for the hosting of the 1973 Amateur World Series, which he was criticized for due to the country still suffering the effects of the 1972 Nicaragua earthquake.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/carlos-garcía-solórzano] He campaigned for the inclusion of baseball in the Olympic Games.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/carlos-garcía-solórzano] While imprisoned in 1980, he was told that the sport would be included at the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, due to the efforts of him and his successor, Robert Smith.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/carlos-garcía-solórzano] An opponent of the Sandinistas, García was accused of heading an anti-communist militia known as the Fuerzas Armadas Democráticas (FAD) before his arrest.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/carlos-garcía-solórzano] He was charged with spying for the CIA and supplying arms to the Contras, though he denied wrongdoing; García was never given a trial, just a 45-minute reading of the charges against him.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/carlos-garcía-solórzano] He was released in 1984, in part due to the efforts of FIFA President João Havelange, and made his way to the United States, where he was welcomed to the White House by Ronald Reagan.
[src:carlos-garcía-solórzano/carlos-garcía-solórzano] García returned to Nicaragua in 1990, after the opposition won the elections, and became minister of the Nicaraguan Sports Institute (IND).
